        {"question": "Is aluminum wiring dangerous?", "answer": "Homes built between 1965-1973 may have aluminum wiring, which is 55x more likely to cause a fire connection point than copper. Warning signs include: warm outlets, flickering lights, burning smells, and scorched outlets. If your home has aluminum wiring, have an electrician evaluate it. Solutions include complete rewiring ($8,000-$20,000) or COPALUM crimp connections ($3,000-$5,000), which are the only EPA-approved repair."},
